{"role": "assistant", "timestamp": "2026-03-29T19:01:14.887686", "content": "```python\n# Ordered list with nested items\nordered = [\n    [\"apple\", 1, {\"color\": \"red\"}],\n    [\"banana\", 2, {\"type\": \"fruit\"}],\n    [\"cherry\", 3, {\"price\": 5.99}]\n]\n\nprint(\"Ordered List:\")\nfor item in ordered:\n    print(item)\n\n# Unordered - note: sets can't contain mutable items like lists/dicts\nunordered = {\n    (\"apple\", 1),       # tuples are hashable (immutable)\n    (\"banana\", 2),      # tuples work\n    (\"cherry\", 3)       # tuples work\n}\n\nprint(\"\\nUnordered Set (using tuples for nesting):\")\nfor item in unordered:\n    print(item)\n\n# Alternative: Use dict for key-value pairs (also unordered insertion pre-3.7, ordered since 3.7+)\nnested_dict = {\n    \"fruit\": [\"apple\", \"banana\"],\n    \"veg\": [\"carrot\", \"broccoli\"]\n}\n\nprint(\"\\nNested Dictionary:\")\nfor key, value in nested_dict.items():\n    print(f\"{key}: {value}\")\n```\n\n---\n\n**Note:** Python sets can't contain mutable items (lists, dicts), so for \"unordered with nesting\" you'd need to use tuples or other immutable types. Dictionaries are the better choice for nested structured data in modern Python."}
